description.text:
Celebrate this Summer with Free Music Performances
Join us for the DSA’s long-running concert series Downtown Summer Sounds, presented by Virginia Mason, and experience free live music at a public space near you. From July 9th to August 23rd, discover a wide range of music performances from local artists such as Whitney Mongé, General Mojo’s, Passenger String Quartet, Bleachbear, and more. With 25 local acts, you’ll find performances for every genre of music, ranging from alternative soul to funk-fusion. Concerts are taking place at 11 locations throughout downtown, including City Hall park, Occidental Square, Denny Park, Westlake Park, and Union Square, so you’ll be sure to be near an amazing performance. All concerts start at noon and each location will offer a variety of food options, free goodies, and a great experience.
 
To see a full lineup, visit: https://downtownseattle.org/events/downtown-summer-sounds/

name.text: Lunch & Learn: Culture Building in a Box
name.html: Lunch & Learn: Culture Building in a Box

description.text:
Are you a manager, entrepreur or HR professional who's committed to building your company's culture? Culture Bites is a new subscription box service that distills research on workplace culture into fun, bite-sized activities that empower personal growth and inclusive teams. Enjoy some pizza while sampling 15-minute activities on burnout, feedback and creativity, and bring a few teammates while you're at it! 

Culture Bites is for managers who are:


Committed to building their team's culture


Willing to invest 15 minutes at a time


Have better things to do than searching online or printing activities



SPEAKER: 
Rob Goehrke has over a decade of experience in creating great team culture. After studying group psychology at Yale, he spent four years in the nonprofit world turning leadership principles into experiential curriculum. Since then, he's managed teams from 5 to 30 employees in both large companies and startups. He received an MBA from Presidio Graduate School (aka BGI/Pinchot), where he leaned the academic and real-world underpinnings to what makes great companies tick. 

Check out www.getculturebites.com

name.text: Holocaust Center for Humanity
name.html: Holocaust Center for Humanity

description.text:
We invite you to tour the Henry and Sandra Friedman Holocaust Center for Humanity, a museum and educational center dedicated to connecting the lessons of the Holocaust to our world today. Through stories and artifacts of local Holocaust survivors, the museum's core exhibit engages visitors in the history of the Holocaust and challenges them to consider how each person's actions make a difference. 
Admission:
Adults: $10 suggested admissionStudents and Seniors: $5 suggested admission
Tickets are for morning (10am-1pm) or afternoon (1pm-4pm) visits. 
All bags are subject to search, and weapons of any type are strictly not allowed in the museum, including guns, knives (even pocket knives), and pepper spray.
 
FAQs
 
What are my transportation/parking options for getting to and from the event?
The Holocaust Center for Humanity is located on the corner of 2nd Ave and Lenora St.
Street parking is available, but be advised that the 2-hour limit is strictly enforced.
Paid Parking Lots:

3rd Ave & Stewart, between 2nd and 3rd. This is a large lot, about 2 blocks from the Holocaust Center. 
Tower 12 Apartments building has a small public parking garage on our block - access through an alley off of Lenora St. west of 2nd Ave.

Public Transit (You can find schedules, maps, and a trip planner on the King County Metro Transit website.)

Nearby stops: 2nd Ave & Lenora St bus stop (on our block), 3rd Ave & Virginia St bus stop (one block away), Westlake Link Light Rail Station (five blocks away, on Pine St between 3rd & 4th Aves).


Do I have to bring my printed ticket to the event?
Printed tickets are not required. As long as you've registered online or via phone we can access your reservation at the front desk.

How can I contact the organizer with any questions?
Call us at 206-582-3000 or email info@holocaustcenterseattle.org.

description.text:
Seattle 101 is our flagship tour! Our unique take on Seattle and your insider’s guide to the Emerald City. Immerse yourself in our beautiful downtown. Stroll through the past in Seattle’s historic Pioneer Square. Walk Seattle’s beautiful waterfront and let the enticing ferries convince you to take a ride. Snap wonderful photos of the skyline, key landmarks and surrounding mountains. Learn about the best happy hours and most engaging activities in town. Don’t just come to Seattle, experience Seattle!
 
 
Highlights:

Downtown Seattle
Seattle’s beautiful waterfront
Seattle's old town Pioneer Square
Photo ops 
Totem poles
Recommendations for Seattle’s best restaurants, pubs, parks and activities
Seattle's unique history and culture!

 
When: Daily Rain or Shine* - Dress to impress Mother Nature
Cost: Pay What You Feel! Our guides work hard to make sure you feel it’s worth every penny.
Where it Starts: Victor Stienbruek Park (2001 Western Ave), between the two totem poles - located at the North entrance to Pike Place Market.
 Reservations recommended. Walk ups are welcome space permitting.
*Tours do not operate in dangerous or severe weather. Tours may also be canceled in rare emergency situations. Check the tour calendar for updated information.

description.text:
June-August: Summer Skin Care and First Aid! We'll make poultices, healing skin salves, and soothing sunburn sprays.I'll teach you how to  make herbal teas, tinctures, or body-care products, depending on the area of focus and applicable treatments. I'll talk about a specific herb, condition, or product, and then we'll get hands-on and have you make your own. I'll teach you how to easily add herbal medicine to your daily routine, in order to increase health and longevity, without buying expensive, and often harmfully artificial, products.
I will  give about a 35-minute talk about a topic that is relevant to the times, be it stress, insomnia, detoxification, gut health, etc. I'll pass around herbs to touch, smell, taste, and feel. You will be provided the materials and containers to take your creations home with you!
For more info, go to www.alimentalherbalism.com.

description.text:
SHARPLY Brewery Summer Tour Stop #11: Obec Brewing
Join us at Obec Brewing on Wednesday, August 21st to shop for the summertime necessities while enjoying a pint. We’re giving 15% off all SHARPLY knits from 4 – 8 pm and the first ten customers to purchase a SHARPLY shirt get a free beer! Plus, enter your email for a chance to win $150 gift card to SHARPLY. We look forward to seeing you there!
When: August 21st, 2019 4pm – 8pm
Where: Obec Brewing, 1144 NW 52nd St, Seattle, WA 98107
About SHARPLY
SHARPLY is a Seattle based men’s lifestyle brand that offers timeless, quality essentials made right here in the USA. Our private label collection includes a wide array of shirts, sweatshirts, and henleys—all of which are incredibly soft and pre-shrunk. We also carry premium denim and accessories from other brand partners. We live to create and supply high-quality knits that men can wear daily, from the boardroom to the brewery. Originally launched as an e-commerce business in 2016, we opened our first retail store on Capitol Hill a year later. Find us online at shopSHARPLY.com or swing by our store in Cap Hill!
About Obec Brewing
Obec Brewing is a 10 barrel brewery and taproom located in the Ballard neighborhood of Seattle. Our personal brewing style is rooted in the history and tradition of beer-craft - a lot of great beers have come before us, and we appreciate the tradition and artistry that created them.
So what is Obec? Obec (pronounced "O-betz") is the Czech word for “community,” plain and simple. name.text: Dynamic Talks: Seattle "ML and Predictive Analytics in the Modern Enterprise"
name.html: Dynamic Talks: Seattle "ML and Predictive Analytics in the Modern Enterprise"

description.text:
Come join us at the fourth event of our free technical meetup series, "Dynamic Talks", in Seattle! 
Dynamic Talks is an ongoing meetup series featuring technical talks from some of the leading experts in tech in major cities around the US. Enjoy talks about the most innovative subjects in: AI, ML, voice platforms, the Cloud and search. One of the objectives of Dynamic Talks is to foster and encourage the local technology community to share knowledge. Every event is free, with complimentary food and drinks.
Topic: "ML and Predictive Analytics in the Modern Enterprise"
Agenda
[5:30pm - 6:00pm]: Guests arrive, food and drinks are served
[6:00pm - 6:30pm]: The first talk will be presented by Eugene Steinberg on “Not Your Father's Search Engine: Deep learning applications for e-commerce search”, followed by a Q&A
[6:30pm - 7:00pm]: The second talk will be presented by Shervin Majd on "Reducing No-shows and Late Cancelations in Healthcare Enterprise", followed by a Q&A
[7:00pm - 7:20pm]: Networking break
[7:20pm - 7:50pm]: The third talk will be presented by Rumi Olsen on " Deep learning with AWS", followed by QA
[7:50pm - 8:20pm]: The fouth talk will be presented by Parag Shrivastava on "Implementing AI for New Business Models and Efficiencies", followed by QA
[8:20pm - 8:30pm]: More networking, closing remarks, and the event concludes
Talk Details
Eugene Steinberg's talk details:
Title: "Not Your Father's Search Engine: Deep Learning Applications for e-Commerce Search"
Abstract: In this talk, we will discuss how recent advancements in artificial intelligence are transforming traditional search technologies. Deep learning-based image analysis and natural language processing open exciting new horizons for search and recommendation applications across the industries. We’ll talk about how deep learning models can help conventional search engines to achieve better relevance. We will share our experience implementing innovative solutions for online retailers, finance and high tech customers.
About Eugene Steinberg:
Eugene Steinberg is a Technical Fellow and founding engineer at Grid Dynamics. As a Principal Architect and Consultant, Eugene has delivered some of the largest Grid Dynamics programs, from inception to production to maturing. He has many interests, including: information retrieval, e-commerce and enterprise search, natural language processing, computer vision, general science, and the art of building scalable distributed systems. Eugene earned a PhD in Applied Math from Saratov State University.
Shervin Majd's talk details:
Title: "Reducing No-shows and Late Cancelations in Healthcare Enterprise"
Abstract: Patient No-shows and Late Cancelations is estimated to cost around $150B across the nation. Providence St. Joseph Health, Healthcare Intelligence Group has been working on this pain point for the past couple of years and has developed a software solution leveraging a predictive engine to identify high risk patients at risk of No-show and Late Cancellation on a daily basis. More than 25 clinics have been using this solution for about 2 years now to optimize their reminder call strategy and to have a meaningful reduction of No-shows and Late Cancellations. In addition, a call center pilot was designed recently to standardize this process end-end. Pilot results will be evaluated to prove the impact at scale.
About Shervin Majd:
Shervin Majd is a Digital Health executive with more than ten years hands-on product and strategy leadership experience collaborating with multidisciplinary teams to develop and launch innovative solutions across the care continuum. Currently, Shervin is an executive member of Providence health and St. Joseph and responsible for development of innovative web/mobile digital health applications and platforms, leveraging near real-time access to data, advanced analytics and predictive data models.Prior to that, he was director of mobile health programs at Nantmobile and a member of the executive team where he was responsible for building digital health and wellness products to empower patients and clinicians. Shervin also worked at Vodafone ventures and was responsible for incubation, domestic and global product launches, as well as strategic investments in mobile health domain. Shervin also serves as a product strategy advisor and mentor for several medical devices and digital health startups in addition to being a member of Life Science Angels Group in the Bay Area, investing in medical devices, digital health and artificial intelligence solutions.
Parag Shrivastava's talk details:
Title: "Implementing AI for New Business Models and Efficiencies"
Abstract: Artificial Intelligence (AI) and data are foundational to ideation of new business models that bring growth and efficiencies. This is in action in pharmaceutical supply chain for reducing costs, increasing volumes, and optimizing the contracts with suppliers. The implementation involves process and tools that make data usable, and overcome the challenges of culture, ethics, data scalability, compute and engineering, and. Learn about data collection, data management, and metadata management tools implementation and modern data architecture to support them. Discuss machine learning algorithms for growth and efficiency scenarios.
About Parag Shrivastava:
Parag is a data architecture and products leader at McKesson, and leads the strategy, implementation, and management of enterprise data. He has led multiple initiatives at McKesson including data analytics for Joint Venture between McKesson and Walmart, wherein the partnership resulted in joint sourcing of Generics Pharmaceutical. He also led Synergy analytics for McKesson’s $8B acquisition in Europe. Prior to McKesson, Parag was a Technology Consulting Manager at Deloitte, primarily focused on data and technology strategy and transformation at large Healthcare provider, payor, and medical device companies, scoping, planning, and implementing the clinical information systems, insurance claims platform stabilization, and business intelligence.
About Rumi Olsen:
Rumi Olsen is a seasoned computer scientist with over a decade of engineering experience. As a Partner Solutions Architect at AWS, she solves day-to-day challenges for cloud builders globally. Rumi has expertise in AWS serverless application development as well as AWS machine learning services.
Parking Information:
There are two nearby garages, directly underneath the building and right across the street. You need to be on Pine Street to enter both garages. Parking for these garages are $6 and $5/ hour respectively, or $18 and $20 dollar for the day.

name.html: The Urbanist: August volunteer event feat. CHRI

description.text:
Join The Urbanist and the Capitol Hill Renter Initiative on August 21st at 5:30pm for our Monthly Volunteer Event! We will be writing letters and emails to City of Seattle leadership, urging them to:


move forward with studying green spaces and transit-oriented design near future Link light-rail stations, with a focus on equity, social justice, and climate change; and


advance the principles and policies of 350 Seattle's Green New Deal and the MASS Coalition's Transportation Package.


Our Monthly Volunteer Event is a great way to get involved with The Urbanist! If you're interested in learning more about us, having an impact in the community, and getting to know other urbanists, then this is a great opportunity. Each event consists of two tasks. The first is providing support to our featured ally organization, and the second task is an Urbanist project. We will provide all materials. Please arrive prepared to help out, make friends, and get a coffee or beer (to support our host venue!). We'll be meeting on August 21 at Cafe Solstice. At our monthly meetings, which are open to the public, we've hosted guest speakers ranging from city planners to tenant organizers to Capitol Hill artists and musicians. We've also organized movie nights, picnics in Cal Anderson Park, and other social gatherings. We envision a Capitol Hill neighborhood with diverse people and housing types; a welcoming, walkable, multimodal, equitable, accessible, and affordable community for all residents.

name.html: Atlas Obscura Society Seattle: Historic Murals of West Seattle

description.text:
With their origins tracing back to the late 1980s, the murals of West Seattle depict glimpses of long gone local history, from Elliott Bay’s once-thriving "mosquito fleet" to the “Old Mud Hole” of Lincoln Park.
Join Atlas Obscura for a fascinating, fact-filled tour of these large-scale artworks found around the Alaska Junction neighborhood of West Seattle with Clay Eals, former editor of the West Seattle Herald and former executive director of the Seattle Southwest Historical Society. You’ll get the whole story of how these murals were created by civic leaders and a team of world-class artists, discover the tricks of their trade, learn which local luminaries were depicted in various scenes, and get more inside scoop on these unique achievements. A portion of the proceeds from this event will be donated to the West Seattle Junction Association’s mural restoration project.
ADDITIONAL DETAILS
• Meet Clay and Field Agent Keith Bacon outside the Post Office at 4412 California Ave SW. • The tour is all outdoors and will last about 90 minutes. Participants will walk approximately 1 mile. Dress appropriately for the weather and wear comfortable shoes. • This event runs rain or shine! • Street parking is available. Please read signs carefully and park at your own discretion. • Metro Routes 37, 50, 55, 128 and Rapid Ride C Line are within a five-minute walk.
QUESTIONS?
Email Keith Bacon at keith.bacon@atlasobscura.com.
Stay connected! Subscribe to the Atlas Obscura Society Seattle newsletter and join  our Facebook group for a first glimpse at upcoming events.
Advance tickets only. All sales final. No refunds or exchanges.

name.text: Seattle Design Festival - Recycling the Beauty of Puget Sound
name.html: Seattle Design Festival - Recycling the Beauty of Puget Sound

description.text:
As part of Design in Public's 2019 Seattle Design Festival, the Seattle 2030 District and Boeing welcome you to explore how we can recycle the beauty of Puget Sound to make Seattle more resilient and sustainable.
This summer, we created a design competition challenging students, engineers, and architects to come up with innovative ways to capture rainwater and reuse it in building operations. These solutions will help mitigate stormwater runoff, conserve of our City's potable water supply, and improve the performance of our buildings. Come engage with the winning design team, who transformed the roof of the Expeditors Headquarters in downtown Seattle into a water recycling project, keeping over 400,000 gallons of stormwater out of our sewers and reducing their demand on municipal supply. There will also be the opportunity to connect with our amazing judges who represent some of the leading sustainability firms in our region. We will also be discussing how these solutions can be replicated throughout Seattle and the pressing need to retrofit Seattle's downtown core to help protect Puget Sound. Come learn how we can transform our buildings to act as trees and help Seattle operate as its natural ecosystem.
Drinks and snacks will be provided. 
Reach out to stevenfry@2030districts.org with any questions.

name.text: FREE Yoga on the Dock
name.html: FREE Yoga on the Dock

description.text:
Join Seattle-based Yoga Instructor and Wellness Coach, Elizabeth Krenke, for the 4th annual Yoga on the Dock series every Wednesday evening June - August at Elliott Bay Marina! 
Yoga isn’t only great for increasing flexibility, building muscle strength, improving bone health and relieving physical pain, but it can also lower blood pressure, relieve depression and make you a happier person. Elizabeth believes wholeheartedly that everyone can benefit from practicing yoga and should have the opportunity to experience it in nature away from the hustle, bustle and busyness of city life!
There’s no better yoga studio than one perched above the glistening waters of Elliott Bay overlooking downtown Seattle, the iconic Space Needle and stunning Mt. Rainier.
---------------------------------------------------
Classes run every Wednesday evening June - August* from 6:30-7:30pm starting on 6/5/19. Please arrive at fuel dock (G-dock by Palisade) by 6:15pm to board the water taxi to observation deck. 
***ALL JULY CLASSES ARE PROUDLY SPONSORED BY GT'S KOMBUCHA PROVIDING EACH YOGI WITH FREE KOMBUCHA...YAY!
All levels are welcome!
*NO CLASSES ON 7/3, 7/31, 8/7
Whether you’re a regular practitioner of yoga or completely new to it, you will leave each class feeling relaxed, renewed and ready to live your best life!
To learn more about Elizabeth Krenke, visit her website @ www.elizabethkrenke.com.

I hereby WAIVE AND RELEASE Elizabeth Krenke Wellness LLC, its owners, officers, employees, and instructors from any claim, demand, cause of action of any kind resulting from or related to my participation in the programs offered at the facility. In taking part in the yoga classes, workshops, or other activities at Elizabeth Krenke Wellness LLC, I understand and acknowledge that I am fully responsible for any and all risks, injuries, or damages, known or unknown, which might occur as a result of my participation in the classes, workshops, or other activities. 
--------------------

FAQs
 
Are there ID or minimum age requirements to enter the event?
Yes, all attendees must be 18 years of age to attend. 
 
What are my transportation/parking options for getting to and from the event?
 There is ample FREE marina parking in the lot behind Palisade Restaurant situated in the middle of Elliott Bay Marina. 
What can I bring into the event?
Yoga mat, water, sunglasses, towel and weather appropriate attire. You will move and possibly even sweat, so wear comfy clothes for yoga or general exercise

elizabeth.krenke@gmail.com

No refunds. All sales are final.

Yes.

Yes. If you have to give up your ticket for any reason please ask the person attending in your place to show the ticket upon arrival.
